      "content": "The heap just keeps growing till it crashes, a classic case of a memory leak, and it's likely due to the fact that you're not properly deallocating memory in your `SensorData` class. You've got a good start with the destructor, but it's not enough. \n\nYou see, just like a goblin's lair is always cluttered with trash, your heap is cluttered with unused memory. The `SensorData` objects are being created and destroyed, but the memory they allocated for the `buffer` is never being freed. \n\nThe issue lies in the fact that you're creating a new `SensorData` object on the heap every time you call `run_sensor_loop()`, but you're not deleting it. It's like a goblin's hoard, where old, useless items are never discarded. \n\nTo fix this, you should consider using smart pointers, like `std::unique_ptr` or `std::shared_ptr`, to manage the memory for you. This way, you can ensure that the memory is properly deallocated when the `SensorData` object is no longer needed. \n\nHere's an example of how you could modify your code to use `std::unique_ptr`:\n\n```cpp",
